Companion dialogue: export the topic/service lists, response text and NPC name to
the bottom screen, and drive topic/service/goodbye selection from there.

Export (all via the companion Debug::Log -> onCompanionLine bridge; streamed as
one small line each to avoid the 4096-byte stdout-flush split):
  * setKeywords()      -> COMPANION_DIALOGUE_START / _TOPIC:<name> / _END
                          (the filtered per-NPC topic list; not exposed to Lua).
  * updateTopicsPane() -> COMPANION_DIALOGUE_SERVICES_START / _SERVICE:<name> / _END
                          (Barter/Spells/Travel/... from getServices(); empty = none;
                          same display strings the buttons use so a tapped service
                          routed back through companionSelectEntry() matches exactly).
  * setPtr()           -> COMPANION_DIALOGUE_NPC:<name> (emitted before startDialogue,
                          new-actor only, so it doubles as the Kotlin history-clear
                          signal that precedes the greeting's first SAY line).
  * addResponse()      -> COMPANION_DIALOGUE_SAY_START / _TOPIC:<title> /
                          _LINE:<one physical line>* / _END, then
                          _LINKS:<pipe-separated> tappable topic phrases from
                          mKeywordSearch.parseHyperText() (the same search the in-game
                          history renders with). Text is split on '\n' before logging
                          because a newline inside one Log() fragments into untagged
                          continuation lines.
  * onClose()          -> COMPANION_DIALOGUE_CLOSED (guarded by containsMode so a
                          pushed service window is not treated as "closed").

Selection: a file-static pointer to the single DialogueWindow (set in its
constructor) plus two extern "C" bridges let drainCompanionCommands()
(androidmain.cpp, engine main thread) drive selection without widening the
WindowManager interface:
  * companionSelectEntry() -> onSelectListItem(), the exact click handler (services
    open their windows, everything else is a topic; same mGoodbye/isInChoice guards).
  * companionGoodbye() mirrors onByeClicked() (Goodbye is not a topic).
Both bridges no-op unless a dialogue is open (stale-mPtr guard).

